It finite jump may occur if 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 has a finite jump or 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}(x)$
\end_inset

 has a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 singularity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we assume that time derivative of the probability is finite at the jump,
 it follows from the continuity equation that the probability flux must
 be 
\series bold
continuous
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S(0_{+},t) & =S(0_{-},t)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

from which follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-D_{2}(0_{+})\left[\Phi_{x}(0_{+})W(0_{+},t)+W(0_{+},t)\right]=-D_{2}(0_{-})\left[\Phi_{x}(0_{-})W(0_{-},t)+W(0_{-},t)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0_{\pm})$
\end_inset

 denotes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\epsilon\rightarrow0}f(\pm\epsilon)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

